The paper deals with the problem of estimating the number of triangles in a graph stream, which is a fundamental problem in graph theory and falls under the category of graph algorithms. The paper proposes a sampling algorithm that is parameterized by the maximum number of triangles sharing a single vertex, which is a technique commonly used in data stream algorithms. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). The paper also discusses the performance of the algorithm on different types of graphs, including random graphs and independent triangles, which suggests that it could be relevant to sub-categories such as cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) and cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory). Additionally, the paper discusses the use of sampling algorithms for triangle counting, which is a topic that falls under the sub-category of cs.SI (Social and Information Networks). Finally, the paper presents a lower bound that applies to all graph classes, which could be relevant to sub-category cs.CC (Computational Complexity).
